    <segment id="1" parent="24" relname="span"> 
 
There is nothing against SSK or social constructivism except
its self-understanding:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="antithesis"> it is not a comprehensive programme
for understanding the development of the sciences.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="1" relname="evidence">  The social
construction of the sciences focusses on a sub-dynamics,
notably its social construction. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="23" relname="span"> The value of its
contribution for STS has been that the programme emphasizes
the contingency of the development, perhaps ad absurdum.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="antithesis">
 
For example, scientific results are not expected to be
symmetrical.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="22" relname="span"> Instead, one expects the scientific relevance of
a scientific discovery to be different from its social or
institutional relevance.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration">  We do not remember Pasteur because
of his role in French politics, but because of his role in
bio-medics.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="antithesis">
 
The crucial point is that knowledge cannot be reduced to an
attribute of authors or their social institutions nor to its
literary manifestations.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="26" relname="span">  On the contrary, as Slezak (1989)
has argued before, one expects a larger variation in the
knowledge content of science than in these other dimensions,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="25" relname="span">
and one should a fortiori not try to explain the larger
variation in terms of the much smaller (&quot;socio-cognitive&quot;)
interaction terms. </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="evaluation"> That is just not good in sociological
terms.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="30" relname="span">
 
In other words, the sciences are not belief systems </segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="12" relname="background">(beliefs
are attributes of human beings or their collectives)</segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="33" relname="span"> but
rational expectation systems. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="antithesis"> The rationality is sometimes
erroneously considered as part of the subject of study
(&quot;scientificiation&quot;),</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="31" relname="span"> but it hopefully remains a property of
the model. </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="34" relname="span"> A construction can always be analysed in terms of
its genesis,</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="32" relname="span"> and indeed that provides us with &quot;nice&quot; stories.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
In my opinion, SSK and other social constructivists have
provided us with case studies, indeed.</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="19" relname="antithesis">
 
Articles in THES and the NYBR do not really help for those who
are not yet &quot;believers&quot;.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="38" relname="span">  My advice would be: stop making
&quot;knowledge claims.&quot; </segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="21" relname="antithesis"> As noted, they play a role in the genesis
of scientific knowledge only. </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="36" relname="span"> The selection processes are
eventually more interesting.</segment>
